# Route Description

## Route Overview

From the parking area, walk south to the east end of Summit Lake \-  3\. Leave the road and hike southwest to the base of a broad slope. Climb 500' up this slope ( 4\) to reach a small bowl below the North Face \-  5\. Again, study the terrain ahead so you know the exact location of the couloir \-  6\. If you haven't already turned on your beacon and strapped on the crampons, this is a good place to do it. Bypass the bowl on the left and then traverse right toward the north face \-  7\. After passing beneath cliffs and rocks, turn left and begin climbing steeper terrain below the entrance to the couloir \-  8\. Continue above 13,700' to reach the more-defined couloir \-  9\.

Above 13,800', the couloir narrows and there are rocks towering over each side \-  10\. Keep climbing toward what appears to be a dead-end above \-  11\. At the top of the couloir, the terrain opens up a bit and becomes a bit steeper \-  12\. Turn right and climb steep snow to reach the exit and easier terrain \-  13 and  14\. Move to the right a bit more, turn left, and continue up to a saddle on the summit ridge \-  15,  16 and  17\. Turn left (east), walk over to the summit trail and ascend the final 100 feet to reach the summit \-  18\. If you're hiking, you can return to Summit Lake via the West Ridge route, over 13er Mt. Spalding.

**Northern Mountains Regional Discussion**  
The snowpack continues its transition from a winter to a spring pack. Water drains as the day warms and then refreezes, leaving large crystals of melt-freeze snow behind and stout crusts in the mornings. Crusts make for efficient over-snow travel early in the day and soft creamy corn riding as just the top inch or two soften. This fun, softer travel window varies from day to day and aspect to aspect. If you miss the window, you could be post-holing deeply into wet snow, which may be the least pleasant and inefficient travel ever known.  
Other than starting and ending your day early, you should be on the lookout for a few different things as you travel in the mountains to maximize safety even more.  
Over the past couple of days, we have received reports of cornices succumbing to gravity. When these massive chunks of snow and ice break off, they unleash a force equivalent to a large bomb hitting the snowpack. This force could potentially blast through crusts, causing a large, deeper avalanche. Even if the cornice doesn’t trigger an avalanche, it could still result in severe injuries or worse. Avoid being on slopes under cornices or getting too close to the edge.

## Objective Hazards

* Rockfall  
* Cornices no  
* Avalanche

## Contingencies & Alternatives

* If couloir conditions are deemed unsafe to climb due to either warm temps or large cornices, we can climb blue sky via spalding east ridge, or gray wolf, or warren and rogers.
